<subSubSection id="C304E3BFEC60FF80FF453D759153FED9" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="69" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA1B034EC60FF83FF453D75973FFE0B" blockId="4.[140,1107,1609,1672]" lastBlockId="5.[140,1108,166,475]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="68" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC60FF82FF453D759267F9B2" bold="true" box="[140,267,1609,1635]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC60FF82FE043D769140F9B5" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Strecker" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[461,556,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudohemihyalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC60FF82FE043D769140F9B5" box="[461,556,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-group can be immediately recognized by the simple, striate forewing pattern (
<figureCitation id="1325ACB1EC60FF82FDFC3D5191F1F959" box="[565,669,1645,1672]" captionStart="Figures 1-5. 1" captionStartId="2.[140,222,1336,1358]" captionTargetBox="[155,1101,181,1299]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[140,1108,165,1316]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figures 1-5. 1a. P. ambigua male (Santa Cruz Co., AZ, USA). 1b. P. ambigua female (Cochise Co., AZ, USA). 2a. P. syracosia male (Zacapa Dpto., Guatemala). 2b. P. syracosia female (Chiapas, Mexico). 3a. P. fallaciosa male (Chiapas, Mexico). 3b. P. fallaciosa female (Zacapa Dpto., Guatemala). 4a. P. sonorosa male paratype (Sonora, Mexico). 4b. P. sonorosa female paratype (Sonora, Mexico). 5. P. potosi male holotype (Nuevo Leon, Mexico)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3810645" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3810645/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Figs. 1-5</figureCitation>
). Internally, the male uncus in dorsal profile is characteristically shaped like a bicycle saddle (Figs. 11-15), with the apex slightly down-turned, pointed and beak-like (Fig. 6). The posterior portion of the uncus consists of two heavily setose, globose or slightly flattened lobes (Fig. 6). The male valve is relatively simple and bipartite (tripartite in most 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FC8E3A2D90CDFEFA" box="[839,929,273,299]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amastus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FC8E3A2D90CDFEFA" box="[839,929,273,299]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Amastus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and a few 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FBD33A2D924CFE9C" baseAuthorityName="Toulgoet" baseAuthorityYear="1994" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudohemihyalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FBD33A2D924CFE9C" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Pseudohemihyalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), with the apical 1/3 to ¼ divided into costal and saccullar processes (figs. 6-10). The transtilla is low, hump-like and finely scobinate (coarsely spinose or scobinate in most other 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FE653A469103FE45" baseAuthorityName="Toulgoet" baseAuthorityYear="1994" box="[428,623,378,404]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudohemihyalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FE653A469103FE45" box="[428,623,378,404]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Pseudohemihyalea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, long, prong-like and variously scobinate in 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FF623AA19269FE66" box="[171,261,413,439]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amastus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FF623AA19269FE66" box="[171,261,413,439]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">Amastus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Female genitalia are relatively simple across the whole 
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FC4E3AA1938AFE0A" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">
Pseudohemihylaea- 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FF453AFD938AFE0A" box="[140,230,449,475]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Amastus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amastus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
group, and no characters were found that distinguish the 
<taxonomicName id="4C1ECBB7EC61FF83FCA23AFC90A6FE0B" authorityName="Schmidt" authorityYear="2009" baseAuthorityName="Strecker" baseAuthorityYear="2009" box="[875,970,448,474]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Pseudohemihyalea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ambigua">
<emphasis id="B96A6C26EC61FF83FCA23AFC90A6FE0B" box="[875,970,448,474]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="68">ambigua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group from
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF61E0BCEC61FF83FF453D0A915DF95D" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3810649" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3810649" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3810649/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="68" startId="5.[140,222,1590,1612]" targetBox="[153,1097,560,1566]" targetPageId="5">
